### Holy Trinity Platt Church

**Holy Trinity Platt Church**, also known by the less specific but equally accurate moniker of **Holy Trinity Church, Rusholme**, stands as a testament to architectural ambition within [Platt Fields Park](/Platt_Fields_Park) in [Rusholme](/Rusholme), [Manchester](/Manchester), England. It’s not just a building; it's an active [Anglican](/Anglican) [parish church](/Parish_church), a functioning part of the [Hulme](/Hulme) deanery, the Manchester archdeaconry, and the wider [diocese of Manchester](/Anglican_Diocese_of_Manchester). Its significance is further cemented by its inclusion in the [National Heritage List for England](/National_Heritage_List_for_England) as a designated Grade II* [listed building](/Listed_building). This designation isn't for its historical gravitas alone, but for its unique construction. It’s the second of [Edmund Sharpe](/Edmund_Sharpe)'s so-called "pot churches," a descriptor derived from its primary building material: [terracotta](/Terracotta). It’s a material choice that, frankly, raises an eyebrow.

#### History

The genesis of Holy Trinity Platt can be traced back to 1845–46, with the architectural vision of [Lancaster](/Lancaster,_Lancashire) architect [Edmund Sharpe](/Edmund_Sharpe). The impetus for its construction came from Thomas Carrill Worsley of [Platt Hall](/Platt_Fields_Park). The Worsley family had a historical connection to the area, their ancestral chapel being [Platt Chapel](/Platt_Chapel). However, by the early 19th century, this chapel had embraced [Unitarianism](/Unitarianism), a theological shift that evidently did not sit well with the Anglican Worsley. This led to Thomas Worsley’s decision to establish a new Anglican church.

His ambition, however, was not entirely unique. He found himself in a peculiar race against a neighbour, a Mr. Anson of Birch Hall, to be the first to build an Anglican church in the vicinity. Anson managed to erect St James' Church on Danes Road, Rusholme, but Worsley, with a strategic flair for the dramatic, ensured Holy Trinity was [consecrated](/Consecration) even before its physical completion. The choice of dedication to the [Holy Trinity](/Trinity) was a deliberate, almost defiant, statement against the Unitarian leanings of the old family chapel. The cost of this audacious undertaking was £4,000, a sum equivalent to approximately £490,000 in 2023, and this figure notably excludes the cost of the stained glass. Upon its completion, the church was designed to accommodate between 650 and 700 parishioners, a respectable capacity for its time.

Sharpe's prior foray into "pot church" architecture was [St Stephen and All Martyrs' Church, Lever Bridge](/St_Stephen_and_All_Martyrs%27_Church,_Lever_Bridge). For Holy Trinity, the terracotta for the main structure was supplied by the Ladyshore Coal and Terra Cotta Company, a business owned by Sharpe's brother-in-law, John Fletcher. However, this familial arrangement was not without its friction, particularly concerning the costs involved. While Fletcher provided the terracotta for the body of the church, the material for the spire was sourced from a different manufacturer, Fletcher's own brother-in-law, Edmund Peel Willock. This divergence in suppliers, it seems, had consequences. The church itself was [consecrated](/Consecration) on 26 June 1846 by the Right Reverend John Bird Sumner, the [Bishop of Chester](/Bishop_of_Chester), yet the spire remained incomplete until 1850. The terracotta used for the spire proved to be of a lesser quality than Fletcher's material, a fact that would necessitate its replacement in 1912. Decades later, in 1966–67, a church hall was erected and integrated with the east wall of the church, a practical addition to the existing structure.

#### Architecture

The defining characteristic of Holy Trinity Platt is its pervasive use of [terracotta](/Terracotta). This material is not confined to the exterior; it forms the facing for the interior spaces as well. The terracotta is meticulously crafted to mimic the appearance of stone, even down to the inclusion of [masons' marks](/Mason%27s_mark), a detail that speaks to a level of intentional imitation. The roof, in contrast, is finished with [slate](/Slate). Architecturally, the church adheres to the [Decorated](/English_Gothic_architecture) style, a testament to Sharpe’s engagement with [Gothic Revival](/Gothic_Revival_architecture) principles.

The layout of the church is a carefully considered arrangement: a five-[bay](/Bay_(architecture)) [nave](/Nave) topped with a [clerestory](/Clerestory), a prominent southwest [steeple](/Steeple_(architecture)), [aisles](/Aisle) extending to the north and south, a two-bay [chancel](/Chancel) at the east end, a west porch for entry, and a south porch ingeniously incorporated within the tower itself. The tower, a substantial structure, rises in three stages, reinforced by angle [buttresses](/Buttress). Its south face features a doorway, and its middle stage is adorned with three-light windows set within [crocketted](/Crocket) [gables](/Gable). Above these are paired openings for the bells. The apex of the tower is crowned with an [embattled](/Battlement) [parapet](/Parapet) and corner [pinnacles](/Pinnacle), lending it a formidable, almost defensive, appearance. Surmounting the tower is a tall, octagonal spire, a dramatic element supported by [flying buttresses](/Flying_buttress). The west window of the church is a four-light composition, while the east window is a more expansive five-light structure, both featuring elaborate [tracery](/Tracery).

##### Interior

Within the church, the use of terracotta continues unabated, even extending to the [piers](/Pier_(architecture)) that support the [arcades](/Arcade_(architecture)). The [font](/Baptismal_font), however, is an exception, rendered in stone and possessing an octagonal bowl. The stained glass within the chancel serves as a memorial to the Worsley family, with its creation dating between 1849 and 1850. In the north aisle, a window from 1871 showcases glasswork by the renowned firm of [Lavers, Barraud and Westlake](/Lavers,_Barraud_and_Westlake).

